10 An Act relating to county resale auctions; amending
68 O.S. 2021, Section 3129, as last amended by
11 Section 4, Chapter 179, O.S.L. 2025 (68 O.S. Supp.
2025, Section 3129), which relates to property bid
12 off in name of county; requiring the Oklahoma Health
Care Authority to release certain liens on certain
13 request of county treasurer; providing for the
Oklahoma Health Care Authority to release certain
14 liens upon request of municipality for certain
purposes; updating statutory language; and providing
15 an effective date.
16
17
18
19 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
20 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 68 O.S. 2021, Section 3129, as
21 last amended by Section 4, Chapter 179, O.S.L. 2025 (68 O.S. Supp.
22 2025, Section 3129), is amended to read as follows:
23 Section 3129. A. On the day real estate is advertised for
24 resale, the county treasurer shall offer same for sale at the office
SB1198 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 of t he county treasurer between the hours of eight a.m. and five
2 p.m., the exact hours of each sale to be determined by the local
3 county treasurer, and continue the sale thereafter from day to day
4 between such hours until all of the real estate is sold and is
5 concluded by the county treasurer. The real estate shall be sold at
6 public auction to the highest bidder for cash or certified funds.
7 Online auctions may accept online payments.
8 B. The county treasurer may choose to hold the June resale
9 through an online auction instead of the in-person process as
10 prescribed in subsection A of this section. Such online auctions
11 shall occur during regular business hours and shall follow all other
12 requirements of the resale auction until all of the real estate is
13 sold and is concluded by the county treasurer. The county treasurer
14 may select a firm to conduct the online auction with the cost of the
15 online auctioneer to be added to the sale of each property.
16 C. 1. As used in this section, “nuisance property” shall be
17 defined as property that is deemed unmarketable or unusable due to
18 the existence of liens in excess of the property’s fair market value
19 as shown by the county assessor’s office or due to environmental
20 problems or conditions that exist on the property that would cost
21 more to remedy than the fair market value of the property as shown
22 by the county assessor’s office, or property in which abatement
23 liens have been placed upon the property by a municipality in excess
24 of twenty-five percent (25%) of the property’s fair market value as
SB1198 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 show n by the county assessor’s office.
2 2. All property must be sold for a sum not less than two-thirds
3 (2/3) of the assessed value of such real estate as fixed for the
4 current fiscal year, or for the total amount of taxes, penalties,
5 interest, and costs due on such property, whichever is the lesser.
6 Notwithstanding, there shall be a reserve minimum bid placed in an
7 amount covering all taxes, abatement costs, penalties, interest, and
8 costs due to a municipality if the right to exercise the reserve
9 minimum bid is noticed to the county treasurer. With the exception
10 of nuisance property, if there is no bid equal to or greater than
11 the sum so required, the county treasurer shall bid off the same in
12 the name of the county. However, the property must be bid off in
13 the name of the municipality if demand is made in writing by a
14 municipality which has outstanding liens upon the property. In
15 cases of nuisance property, the county treasurer shall have
16 discretion to not bid off the property in the name of the county and
17 instead allow the property to remain under its current ownership,
18 unless demand is made in writing by a municipality which has
19 outstanding liens upon the property. “Nuisance property” shall be
20 defined as property that is deemed unmarketable or unusable due to
21 the existence of liens in excess of the property’s fair market value
22 as shown by the county assessor’s office or due to environmental
23 problems or conditions that exist on the property that would cost
24 more to remedy than the fair market value of the property as shown
SB1198 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 by t he county assessor’s office, or property in which abatement
2 liens have been placed upon the property by a municipality in excess
3 of twenty-five percent (25%) of the property’s fair market value as
4 shown by the county assessor’s office. Greenbelts, common areas,
5 easements, retention ponds, and detention ponds may also be
6 considered nuisance property if transference of ownership to either
7 the county or a third party would cause a hardship to the
8 neighborhood or subdivision these areas were meant to serve or to
9 the county or third party.
10 3. The county treasurer shall make the determination, in
11 conjunction with review and approval of the board of county
12 commissioners, upon consideration of the above factors provisions of
13 paragraphs 1 and 2 of this subsection, as to whether or not property
14 constitutes nuisance property. The said nuisance property
15 determination may be made at any time during the year, including
16 before or immediately after the June resale. In the case of a
17 nuisance property that has liens from a city or town, if a minimum
18 bid is not made, the city or town shall be credited a bid on the
19 property equal to the amount of the lien of the city or town if its
20 intention to do so is made known to the county treasurer prior to
21 the sale or at the sale.
22 4. In the case of a nuisance property with liens from a city or
23 town, if a minimum bid is not made, the nuisance property shall be
24 bid off in the name of the city or town if its intention to do so is
SB1198 HFLR Page 4
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 made known to the county treasurer prior to the sale or at the sale.
2 All property bid off in the name of the county shall be for the
3 amount of all taxes, penalties, interest, and costs due thereon, and
4 the county treasurer shall issue a deed therefor to the board of
5 county commissioners for the use and benefit of the county. All
6 nuisance property bid off in the name of the city or town shall be
7 for the amount of any municipal liens due thereon, and the county
8 treasurer shall issue a deed therefor to the city or town for the
9 use and benefit of the city or town.
10 D. The county treasurers shall provide to the Oklahoma Health
11 Care Authority (OHCA) a list of properties that will be sold at tax
12 resales in their respective counties. Using the information
13 provided, the OHCA shall produce a list for each county of
14 properties on which the OHCA has liens. The county treasurers shall
15 make the list of properties with the OHCA liens available to
16 potential buyers at the tax resales. The OHCA shall file a release
17 of the liens on properties that fit the definition of blighted
18 properties, as defined in Section 38-101 of Title 11 of the Oklahoma
19 Statutes, in the county records of the county where the property is
20 located on which OHCA has liens upon request of that county’s
21 treasurer. The OHCA shall additionally file a release of the liens
22 on properties on which OHCA has liens upon request of a municipality
23 if the property is owned by such municipality and is to be
24 transferred to a not-for-profit entity for a qualified project, as
SB1198 HFLR Page 5
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 defi ned in Section 2357.403 of this title, or for another public
2 purpose deemed suitable by the municipality. The filing of the lien
3 release shall not extinguish the debt owed to the OHCA, which may be
4 enforced through any legal means available to the OHCA.
5 E. The county shall not be liable to the state or any taxing
6 district thereof for any part of the amount for which any property
7 may be sold to such county. All property bid off in the name of the
8 county shall be exempt from ad valorem taxation as long as title is
9 held for the county.
10 F. 1. The county shall not be civilly liable for any
11 environmental problems or conditions on any property which that
12 existed on the property prior to the county’s involuntary ownership
13 of the property pursuant to this section, or which that may result
14 from such environmental problems or conditions on the property.
15 During the period of the county’s involuntary ownership of the
16 property, the person or persons who would be legally liable for the
17 environmental problems or conditions on the property but for the
18 county’s ownership shall continue to be liable for such
19 environmental problems or conditions.
20 2. In addition, the county shall not be subject to civil
21 liability with regard to any actions taken by the county to
22 remediate any problems or conditions on the property resulting from
23 the environmental problems or conditions if the remedial action is
24 not performed in a reckless or negligent manner.
SB1198 HFLR Page 6
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
